ce:section.ce:para:
CDs are prepared by one-pot room-temperature Schiff base reaction using TA and EDA. In alkaline EDA aqueous solution, the TA molecule with phenolic groups ( Fig. S1 ) can be easily turned to an oxidized TA with α-hydroxy-ortho-quinone structure ( Fig. S2 ) [25]. After that, CO group of the oxidized TA can react with the N-H2 group of EDA by Schiff base condensation at room temperature to form a crosslinked network structure, which results in the further formation of CDs ( Fig. 1 a) [13]. Therefore, the formation of CDs is directly attributed to the imine bond crosslinking between TA and EDA. TEM image shows the size of the CDs that ranges from 3 to 10 nm with an average diameter of about 5 nm ( Fig. 1 b). High-resolution TEM image ( Fig. 1 c) further reveals that the prepared CDs have an amorphous “wool”-liked structure and are consisted of aggregated or cross-linked monomers or linear polymers, indicating that the obtained CDs belong to amorphous CDs without any lattice fringes.[26] Raman spectrum is used to further reveal the structural feature of CDs. A high intensity ratio (I D/I G = 0.94) of the D band (disorder) to the G band (crystalline) indicates that the prepared CDs have a disordered carbon structure (
Fig. S3
).[27].

Imine bond as the dynamic covalent bond is sensitive to the pH of solution, thus we investigate the effect of acid/alkali solution on the structure and FL of CDs. The proposed CDs have good stability, and the FL hardly changes with the increase of storage time (
Fig. S4
), suggesting that the CDs will not self-decompose in aqueous solution. Under acid solution, the luminescent efficiency of CDs is improved significantly with the increase of the HCl concentration ( Fig. 3
a), which is directly attributed to the increased conjugated system by strong protonation [34]. The red-shifted absorption spectra (
Fig. S5
) of CDs as the increase of acid concentration strongly confirm that the protonation can cause the increase of conjugation degree of CDs. Moreover, the protonation process increases the FL lifetime of CDs from about 4.5 ns (control) to 8.9 ns (0.1 M HCl) ( Fig. 3 b and Table S3). Meanwhile, the protonation of defect sites like phenolate can also increase the FL intensity of CDs.[35] However, HCl solution with too high concentration (1 M, Fig. 3 a) cannot continue to enhance the FL intensity of CDs because the imine bond is unstable in strong acid and easy to acidolysis. The photostability of CDs under different acid concentrations is further investigated (
Fig. S6
). CDs have good photostability in low concentration HCl solution (1 μM and 1 mM), and the FL intensity hardly changes under 60 min of UV illumination. At high concentration of HCl solution (1 M), the FL intensity of CDs decreases slowly with the increase of illumination time, which may be due to the acidolysis-induced FL quenching.

The FL behavior of CDs under alkali solution is completely different with that of CDs under acid solution. The low concentrations of NaOH (1–100 μM) deprotonate the CDs, but hardly affect the luminescence of the CDs ( Fig. 3 a). However, the FL of the CDs can be greatly quenched with the increase of NaOH concentrations (1 mM–1 M). FL emission spectra (
Fig. S7
) of CDs under acid and alkali solution clearly reveal this difference. Under acidic conditions, the FL intensity of CDs first increases and then decreases with the increase of HCl concentration. While the FL intensity of CDs will continue to decrease with the increase of NaOH concentration. Moreover, FL intensity of CDs in 1 M NaOH solution is significantly lower than that of CDs in 1 M HCl solution, indicating that CDs are easier to be depolymerized by alkaline hydrolysis. Meanwhile, we have used the absorption spectra to monitor the structural changes of CDs in alkali solution ( Fig. 3 c). Our results show that at low concentrations of NaOH (1–100 μM), there are no obvious change in the peak position, providing no effect on the structure of CDs. In contrast, at high concentrations of NaOH (1 mM–1 M), the absorption peak at about 260 nm originated from CDs completely disappears and a new peak at 279 nm appears, suggesting the cleavage of imine bond and re-formation of oxidized TA and EDA. Accordingly, we have designed a control experiment to investigate the absorption spectrum of TA after incubation with H2O2 solution for 1 day. The oxidized TA shows an obvious absorption peak at about 276 nm (
Fig. S8
), confirming our hypothesis of the imine bond cleavage and re-formation of oxidized TA.[36] Meanwhile, with the increase of depolymerization degree, FL lifetime of CDs gradually decreases from about 4.5 ns (control) to 1.8 ns at 1 M NaOH ( Fig. 3 d and Table S4). Because the structure and FL mechanism of CDs are not clear, more studies on the relationship between FL lifetime and pH change is still necessary in future research. These results suggest that the imine bond in CDs in high concentrations (1 mM–1 M) of NaOH can be hydrolyzed to carbonyl group (CO) by alkaline hydrolysis, causing the depolymerization of CDs.

The degree of polymerization of CDs, namely the change of the size of CDs in the process of depolymerization and polymerization, is further measured by TEM and DLS techniques. TEM images of CDs after the addition of NaOH and HCl clearly reveal their depolymerization and polymerization process (
Fig. S9
). After the introduction of NaOH solution (1 M), the size of CDs decreases significantly, indicating the alkaline hydrolysis-induced depolymerization of CDs. After acid neutralization, the size of CDs is basically restored to the original level. The hydrodynamic size measured by DLS is used to evaluate the degree of polymerization of CDs ( Fig. 3 g). The hydrodynamic size of initial CDs solution is about 350 nm. After the introduction of NaOH (1 M), the hydrodynamic size decreases rapidly to about 50 nm because of the depolymerization of CDs. After acid neutralization, the hydrodynamic size increases to about 300 nm, suggesting the re-polymerization of CDs. Meanwhile, the depolymerization of the prepared CDs is accompanied by the decrease of FL intensity, while the re-polymerization of CDs after neutralization with HCl solution will lead to the recovery of the FL intensity of the prepared CDs. The change of the hydrodynamic size and the corresponding FL intensity indicates that the prepared CDs have a polymerization-induced emission effect. Meanwhile, the reversible change (
Fig. S10
) of XPS spectra of CDs further confirms the pH-controlled reversible polymerization of CDs. The prepared CDs have carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen elements. After adding NaOH solution (1 M), the nitrogen element disappears, suggesting the hydrolysis of CN bond and the depolymerization of CDs. While the N1s peak reappears when neutralized by HCl (1 M), which implies the re-formation of CDs. All these results clearly confirms that the reversible polymerization of CDs can be achieved by pH-controlled reversible CN bond cleavage and re-formation ( Fig. 3 h).
